-- `teleport` (Teleport module) is the checked mobility boundary. It runs a
-- portable, single-use closure -- one that captures only content-addressed code
-- and portable data, invoked at most once, so it is safe to move to a fresh
-- runtime. The compiler proves the `@ {once, portable}` contract at each call;
-- running a teleported closure is observationally identical to calling it, so it
-- threads no differently on the two backends. Compose it with `Replay.record`
-- for a durable, replayable mobile run.
import Teleport (..)

fn double(n : Int) : Int = n + n

-- A teleported closure may call top-level functions (code references) freely.
fn moved(x : Int) : Int = teleport(\() -> double(x) + 1)

fn main() =
  println(teleport(\() -> double(20)))
  println(moved(5))
